04598nam a22005415i 9780773571891DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20042004xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735718917 a10.1515/97807735718912doi  a(DE-B1597)657982  a(OCoLC)123470226  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHV6535.C32bY85 2004eb 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a364.152/3/0971911 aCoates, Ken S., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aStrange Things Done :bMurder in Yukon History /cWilliam R. Morrison, Ken S. Coates. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2004] 4cÂ©2004  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b10 Black & white photographs  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMcGill-Queen's Indigenous and Northern Studies ;v4000tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations and Maps -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tThe Yukon -- tIn the Heat of the Rush: The Nantuck Brothers -- tThey Always Get Their Man: Fournier and Labelle -- tBreaking the Faith: The Elfors Case -- tThe Foreign Madman: Alexander Gogoff -- t"To Make These Tribes Understand": The Trial of Alikomiak and Tatamigana -- t"A Drunken Impulse": The Paddy Duncan Case -- tA Miscellany of Murder -- tConclusion -- tStudying Violent Death: An Analysis of Historical Scholarship on Murder -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aKlondike lore is full of accounts of the exploits of Dangerous Dan McGrew, Sergeant Preston of the Mounted, and the Mad Trapper of Rat River. The stories vary from outright fabrications to northern fantasies and, on occasion, real-life accounts. Strange Things Done investigates a series of murders in the pre-World War II Yukon, exploring the boundaries between myths and historical events. The book seeks to understand both the specific events, carefully reconstructed from court evidence and police records, and the broader social and cultural context within which these violent deaths occurred. The murder case studies provide a unique and penetrating perspective on key aspects of Yukon history, such as Native-newcomer relations, mental illness and the folklore about cabin fever, the role of immigrants in northern society, violence in the gold fields, and the role of the police and courts in regulating social behaviour. The investigation of these capital cases also illustrates the fear and paranoia which gripped the territory in the aftermath of a murder, and the societys insistence on quick and retributive justice when offenders were caught and convicted. The Yukon experienced fewer murders than popular literature would suggest, and fewer than most would expect given the region's intense and dramatic history, but those that did occur illustrate the passions, frustrations, angers and human frailties that are present in all societies. The manner in which the murders occurred and the way in which Yukoners reacted also reveals specific and important aspects of territorial society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aCoates, Ken S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMorrison, William R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780773571891?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773571891423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773571891/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11